From Rich Haller Subject Resound Hearing aids and others I have a fairly severe high frequency hearing A recent rough test showed a gently sloping loss to down at Then it falls off a cliff to down from This type of loss is difficult to I am currently using some old siemens behind the ear aids which keep me roughly functional but leave a lot to be Recently I had an opportunity to test the Widex behind the ear aids for several These have four independent programs which are intended to be customized for different hearing situations and can be I found them to be a definite improvement over my current aids and was about to go ahead with them until another local outfit advertised a free trial of another programmable system called Unfortunately I was only able to try the ReSound aids in their office for about minutes and I couldn't compare them 'head to head' with the Nevertheless it did appear to me that they were superior and I was impressed by what I was able to read about the theory behind them which I will give in a separate They also carry the Widex aids and had one patient presumably wealthy who decided to go ahead and get the ReSound even though he had purchased the Widex only months The problem is that the ReSound aids are about twice as expensive as the Widex and other programmable I could take a trip to Europe on the difference Being a lover of bargains and hating to spend money I am having a hard time persuading myself to go with the I would appreciate any opinions on this and other hearing aids and projections about when and if I might see improvements in technology that aren't quite so Rich Haller University of Oregon Eugene OR USA